# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: emscripten
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:emscripten/about-emscripten] Emscripten is a complete Open Source compiler toolchain to WebAssembly.
[src:emscripten/about-emscripten] Practically any **portable** C or C++ codebase can be compiled into WebAssembly using Emscripten, ranging from high-performance games that need to render graphics, play sounds, and load and process files, through to application frameworks like Qt.
[src:emscripten/about-emscripten] Emscripten has already been used to convert a very long list of real-world codebases to WebAssembly, including commercial codebases like the Unreal Engine 4 and the Unity engine.
[src:emscripten/about-emscripten] For examples and demos, see the community-maintained list on the wiki.
[src:emscripten/about-emscripten] Emscripten generates small and fast code!
[src:emscripten/about-emscripten] Its default output format is WebAssembly , a highly optimizable executable format, that runs almost as fast as native code, while being portable and safe.
[src:emscripten/about-emscripten] Emscripten does a lot of optimization work for you automatically, by careful integration with LLVM, Binaryen, Closure Compiler, and other tools.
[src:emscripten/about-emscripten] A high level view of the Emscripten toolchain is given below.
[src:emscripten/about-emscripten] The main tool is the Emscripten Compiler Frontend (emcc).
[src:emscripten/about-emscripten] This is a drop-in replacement for a standard compiler like *gcc* or *clang*.
[src:emscripten/about-emscripten] The Emscripten SDK is used to install the entire toolchain, including emcc and LLVM and so forth.
[src:emscripten/about-emscripten] The Emscripten SDK (emsdk) can be used on Linux, Windows or MacOS.
[src:emscripten/about-emscripten] Emscripten support for **portable** C/C++ code is fairly comprehensive.
[src:emscripten/about-emscripten] Support for the C standard library, C++ standard library, C++ exceptions, etc. is very good, as is SDL2 and other APIs.
[src:emscripten/about-emscripten] OpenGL support in Emscripten support is excellent for OpenGL ES 2.0-type code, and acceptable for other types.
[src:emscripten/about-emscripten] There are differences between the native and Emscripten Runtime Environment, which mean some changes usually need to be made to the native code.
[src:emscripten/about-emscripten] That said, many applications will only need to change the way they define their main loop, and also modify their file handling to adapt to the limitations of the browser/JavaScript.
[src:emscripten/about-emscripten] There are also limitations that can make some code easier to port — read Portability Guidelines to determine where you may need to spend more effort.
[src:emscripten/emscripten] Emscripten allows applications and libraries written in C or C++ to be compiled ahead of time and run efficiently in web browsers, typically at speeds comparable to or faster than interpreted or dynamically compiled JavaScript.
[src:emscripten/emscripten] It even emulates an entire POSIX operating system, enabling programmers to use functions from the C standard library (libc).
[src:emscripten/emscripten] With the more recent development of the WebAssembly System Interface (WASI) and WebAssembly runtimes such as Node.js, Wasmtime, and Wasmer, Emscripten can also be used to compile to WebAssembly for execution in non-web embeddings as well.
[src:emscripten/emscripten] Emscripten has been used to port a number of C/C++ code bases to WebAssembly, including Unreal Engine 3, SQLite, MeshLab, Bullet physics, AutoCAD, and a subset of the Qt application framework.
[src:emscripten/emscripten] The Unity, Defold, and Godot game engines provide an export option to HTML5, utilizing Emscripten.
[src:emscripten/emscripten] Unreal Engine had this export option but it has been migrated out of the engine to a community member plug in.
[src:emscripten/emscripten] The Source Engine, has a community developed port for Emscripten dubbed "HalfLife2JS".
[src:emscripten/emscripten] openFrameworks exports native C++ applications to HTML5 via Emscripten. emscripten-qt permits compiling applications written using the Qt application framework to WebAssembly.
[src:emscripten/emscripten] In December 2014, the Internet Archive launched a DOSBox emulator compiled in Emscripten to provide browser-based access to thousands of archived MS-DOS and PC programs.
[src:emscripten/emscripten] Emscripten was created by Alon Zakai in 2010, motivated by his desire to port his fork of the open-source first-person shooter game *Sauerbraten*, known as *Syntensity*, to the web.
[src:emscripten/emscripten] *Sauerbraten* (also known as *Cube 2*) is an open-source FPS game, and *Syntensity* was Zakai's project that extended the Cube 2 Engine for greater flexibility.
[src:emscripten/emscripten] Observing the increasing shift of applications to web browsers, Zakai began developing Emscripten as an LLVM-to-JavaScript compiler, aiming to make it possible to run existing C and C++ code, such as game engines, directly in the browser.
[src:emscripten/emscripten] In early blog posts, Zakai explained that his long-term goal was "to run Syntensity, or a smaller version of it, on the web", and Emscripten was released as open source shortly after its initial development, making it available for the broader community to experiment with and contribute to.
[src:emscripten/llvm] LLVM is written in C++ and is designed for compile-time, link-time, and runtime optimization.
[src:emscripten/llvm] The LLVM project started in 2000 at the University of Illinois Urbana–Champaign, under the direction of Vikram Adve and Chris Lattner.
[src:emscripten/llvm] LLVM was originally developed as a research infrastructure to investigate dynamic compilation techniques for static and dynamic programming languages.
[src:emscripten/llvm] LLVM was released under the University of Illinois/NCSA Open Source License, a permissive free software licence.
[src:emscripten/llvm] In 2005, Apple Inc. hired Lattner and formed a team to work on the LLVM system for various uses within Apple's development systems.
[src:emscripten/llvm] LLVM has been an integral part of Apple's Xcode development tools for macOS and iOS since Xcode 4 in 2011.
[src:emscripten/llvm] In 2006, Lattner started working on a new project named Clang.
[src:emscripten/llvm] The combination of the Clang frontend and LLVM backend is named Clang/LLVM or simply Clang.
[src:emscripten/llvm] The name *LLVM* was originally an initialism for *Low Level Virtual Machine*.
[src:emscripten/llvm] However, the LLVM project evolved into an umbrella project that has little relationship to what most current developers think of as a virtual machine.
[src:emscripten/llvm] This made the initialism "confusing" and "inappropriate", and since 2011 LLVM is "officially no longer an acronym", but a brand that applies to the LLVM umbrella project.
[src:emscripten/llvm] The project encompasses the LLVM intermediate representation (IR), the LLVM debugger, the LLVM implementation of the C++ Standard Library (with full support of C++11 and C++14), etc.
[src:emscripten/llvm] LLVM is administered by the LLVM Foundation.
[src:emscripten/llvm] Compiler engineer Tanya Lattner became its president in 2014 and was still president and Executive Director as of November 2025.
[src:emscripten/llvm] The project was originally available under the UIUC license.
[src:emscripten/llvm] After v9.0.0 released in 2019, LLVM relicensed to the Apache License 2.0 with LLVM Exceptions.
[src:emscripten/llvm] As of November 2022 about 400 contributions had not been relicensed.
[src:emscripten/llvm] LLVM can provide the middle layers of a complete compiler system, taking intermediate representation (IR) code from a compiler and emitting an optimized IR.
[src:emscripten/llvm] This new IR can then be converted and linked into machine-dependent assembly language code for a target platform.
[src:emscripten/llvm] LLVM can accept the IR from the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) toolchain, allowing it to be used with a wide array of extant compiler front-ends written for that project.
[src:emscripten/llvm] LLVM can also be built with gcc after version 7.5.
[src:emscripten/llvm] LLVM can also generate relocatable machine code at compile-time or link-time or even binary machine code at runtime.
[src:emscripten/llvm] LLVM supports a language-independent instruction set and type system.
[src:emscripten/llvm] Each instruction is in static single assignment form (SSA), meaning that each variable (called a typed register) is assigned once and then frozen.
[src:emscripten/llvm] This helps simplify the analysis of dependencies among variables.
[src:emscripten/llvm] LLVM allows code to be compiled statically, as it is under the traditional GCC system, or left for late-compiling from the IR to machine code via just-in-time compilation (JIT), similar to Java.
[src:emscripten/llvm] The type system consists of basic types such as integer or floating-point numbers and five derived types: pointers, arrays, vectors, structures, and functions.
[src:emscripten/llvm] A type construct in a concrete language can be represented by combining these basic types in LLVM.
[src:emscripten/llvm] For example, a class in C++ can be represented by a mix of structures, functions and arrays of function pointers.
[src:emscripten/llvm] The LLVM JIT compiler can optimize unneeded static branches out of a program at runtime, and thus is useful for partial evaluation in cases where a program has many options, most of which can easily be determined unneeded in a specific environment.
[src:emscripten/llvm] This feature is used in the OpenGL pipeline of Mac OS X Leopard (v10.5) to provide support for missing hardware features.
[src:emscripten/llvm] Graphics code within the OpenGL stack can be left in intermediate representation and then compiled when run on the target machine.
[src:emscripten/llvm] On systems with high-end graphics processing units (GPUs), the resulting code remains quite thin, passing the instructions on to the GPU with minimal changes.
[src:emscripten/llvm] On systems with low-end GPUs, LLVM will compile optional procedures that run on the local central processing unit (CPU) that emulate instructions that the GPU cannot run internally.
[src:emscripten/llvm] LLVM improved performance on low-end machines using Intel GMA chipsets.
[src:emscripten/llvm] A similar system was developed under the Gallium3D LLVMpipe, and incorporated into the GNOME shell to allow it to run without a proper 3D hardware driver loaded.
[src:emscripten/llvm] In 2011, programs compiled by GCC outperformed those from LLVM by 10%, on average.
[src:emscripten/llvm] In 2013, phoronix reported that LLVM had caught up with GCC, compiling binaries of approximately equal performance.
[src:emscripten/llvm] LLVM has become an umbrella project containing multiple components.
[src:emscripten/llvm] LLVM was originally written to be a replacement for the extant code generator in the GCC stack, and many of the GCC frontends were modified to work with it, resulting in the now-defunct LLVM-GCC suite.
[src:emscripten/llvm] The modifications generally involved a GIMPLE-to-LLVM IR step so that LLVM optimizers and codegen could be used instead of GCC's GIMPLE system.
[src:emscripten/llvm] Apple was a significant user of LLVM-GCC through Xcode 4.x (2013).
[src:emscripten/llvm] This use of the GCC frontend was considered a temporary measure; it became mostly obsolete with Apple's development of Clang, a newer compiler frontend, with a more modern, modular codebase and greater compilation speed, supporting C, C++, and Objective-C.
[src:emscripten/llvm] Support for LLVM-GCC was dropped in Xcode 5.
[src:emscripten/llvm] Primarily supported by Apple, Clang was aimed at replacing the C/Objective-C compiler in the GCC system with a system that is more easily integrated with integrated development environments (IDEs) and has wider support for multithreading.
[src:emscripten/llvm] Support for OpenMP directives has been included in Clang since release 3.8.
[src:emscripten/llvm] Widespread interest in LLVM has led to several efforts to develop new frontends for many other languages, including Ada, D, Delphi, Fortran, Haskell, Julia, Rust, Swift, and others.
[src:emscripten/llvm] The Utrecht Haskell compiler can generate code for LLVM.
[src:emscripten/llvm] While the generator was in early stages of development, in many cases it was more efficient than the C code generator.
[src:emscripten/llvm] The Glasgow Haskell Compiler (GHC) backend uses LLVM and achieves a 30% speed-up of compiled code relative to native code compiling via GHC or C code generation followed by compiling, missing only one of the many optimizing techniques implemented by the GHC.
[src:emscripten/llvm] Many other components are in various stages of development, including, but not limited to, a Java bytecode frontend, a Common Intermediate Language (CIL) frontend, the MacRuby implementation of Ruby 1.9, various frontends for Standard ML, and a new graph coloring register allocator.
[src:emscripten/llvm] The core of LLVM is the intermediate representation (IR), a low-level programming language similar to assembly.
[src:emscripten/llvm] IR is a strongly typed reduced instruction set computer (RISC) instruction set which abstracts away most details of the target.
[src:emscripten/llvm] For example, the calling convention is abstracted through `call` and `ret` instructions with explicit arguments.
[src:emscripten/llvm] Also, instead of a fixed set of registers, IR uses an infinite set of temporaries of the form %0, %1, etc.
[src:emscripten/llvm] LLVM supports three equivalent forms of IR: a human-readable assembly format, an in-memory format suitable for frontends, and a dense bitcode format for serializing.
[src:emscripten/llvm] The many different conventions used and features provided by different targets mean that LLVM cannot truly produce a target-independent IR and retarget it without breaking some established rules.
[src:emscripten/llvm] Examples of target dependence beyond what is explicitly mentioned in the documentation can be found in a 2011 proposal for "wordcode", a fully target-independent variant of LLVM IR intended for online distribution.
[src:emscripten/llvm] The LLVM project also introduces another type of intermediate representation named MLIR which helps build reusable and extensible compiler infrastructure by employing a plugin architecture named Dialect.
[src:emscripten/llvm] It enables the use of higher-level information on the program structure in the process of optimization including polyhedral compilation.
[src:emscripten/llvm] Some features are not available on some platforms.
[src:emscripten/llvm] Most features are present for IA-32, x86-64, z/Architecture, ARM, and PowerPC.
[src:emscripten/llvm] In the past, LLVM also supported other backends, fully or partially, including C backend, Cell SPU, mblaze (MicroBlaze), AMD R600, DEC/Compaq Alpha (Alpha AXP) and Nios2, but that hardware is mostly obsolete, and LLVM developers decided the support and maintenance costs were no longer justified.
[src:emscripten/llvm] LLVM also supports WebAssembly as a target, enabling compiled programs to execute in WebAssembly-enabled environments such as Google Chrome / Chromium, Firefox, Microsoft Edge, Apple Safari or WAVM.
[src:emscripten/llvm] LLVM-compliant WebAssembly compilers typically support mostly unmodified source code written in C, C++, D, Rust, Nim, Kotlin and several other languages.
[src:emscripten/llvm] The LLVM machine code (MC) subproject is LLVM's framework for translating machine instructions between textual forms and machine code.
[src:emscripten/llvm] Formerly, LLVM relied on the system assembler, or one provided by a toolchain, to translate assembly into machine code.
[src:emscripten/llvm] LLVM MC's integrated assembler supports most LLVM targets, including IA-32, x86-64, ARM, and ARM64.
[src:emscripten/llvm] For some targets, including the various MIPS instruction sets, integrated assembly support is usable but still in the beta stage.
[src:emscripten/llvm] The lld subproject is an attempt to develop a built-in, platform-independent linker for LLVM. lld aims to remove dependence on a third-party linker.
[src:emscripten/llvm] As of May 2017, lld supports ELF, PE/COFF, Mach-O, and WebAssembly in descending order of completeness. lld is faster than both flavors of GNU ld.
[src:emscripten/llvm] Unlike the GNU linkers, lld has built-in support for link-time optimization (LTO).
[src:emscripten/llvm] This allows for faster code generation as it bypasses the use of a linker plugin, but on the other hand prohibits interoperability with other flavors of LTO.
[src:emscripten/llvm] The LLVM project includes an implementation of the C++ Standard Library named libc++, dual-licensed under the MIT License and the UIUC license.
[src:emscripten/llvm] Since v9.0.0, it was relicensed to the Apache License 2.0 with LLVM Exceptions.
[src:emscripten/llvm] This implements a suite of cache-locality optimizations as well as auto-parallelism and vectorization using a polyhedral model.
[src:emscripten/llvm] llvm-libc is an incomplete, upcoming, ABI independent C standard library designed by and for the LLVM project.
[src:emscripten/llvm] Due to its permissive license, many vendors release their own tuned forks of LLVM.
[src:emscripten/llvm] This is officially recognized by LLVM's documentation, which suggests against using version numbers in feature checks for this reason.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] When operating systems of the same family are installed on two computers with processors with similar instruction sets it is often possible to transfer the files implementing program files between them.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] In the simplest case, the file or files may simply be copied from one machine to the other.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] However, in many cases, the software is installed on a computer in a way which depends upon its detailed hardware, software, and setup, with device drivers for particular devices, using installed operating system and supporting software components, and using different drives or directories.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] In some cases, software, usually described as "portable software", is specifically designed to run on different computers with compatible operating systems and processors, without any machine-dependent installation.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] Porting is no more than transferring specified directories and their contents.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] Software installed on portable mass storage devices such as USB sticks can be used on any compatible computer on simply plugging the storage device in, and stores all configuration information on the removable device.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] Hardware- and software-specific information is often stored in configuration files in specified locations such as the registry on Windows).
[src:emscripten/software-portability] Software which is not portable in this sense must be modified much more to support the environment on the destination machine.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] As of 2011 the majority of desktop and laptop computers used microprocessors compatible with the 32- and 64-bit x86 instruction sets.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] Smaller portable devices use processors with different and incompatible instruction sets, such as ARM.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] The difference between larger and smaller devices is such that detailed software operation is different; an application designed to display suitably on a large screen cannot simply be ported to a pocket-sized smartphone with a tiny screen even if the functionality is similar.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] Web applications are required to be processor independent, so portability can be achieved by using web programming techniques, writing in JavaScript.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] Such a program can run in a common web browser.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] Such web applications must, for security reasons, have limited control over the host computer, especially regarding reading and writing files.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] Non-web programs, installed upon a computer in the normal manner, can have more control, and yet achieve system portability by linking to portable libraries providing the same interface on different systems.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] Software can be compiled and linked from source code for different operating systems and processors if written in a programming language supporting compilation for the platforms.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] This is usually a task for the program developers; typical users have neither access to the source code nor the required skills.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] In open-source environments such as Linux the source code is available to all.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] In earlier days source code was often distributed in a standardised format, and could be built into executable code with a standard Make tool for any particular system by moderately knowledgeable users if no errors occurred during the build.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] Some Linux distributions distribute software to users in source form.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] In these cases there is usually no need for detailed adaptation of the software for the system; it is distributed in a way which modifies the compilation process to match the system.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] Even with seemingly portable languages like C and C++, the effort to port source code can vary considerably.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] Sometimes the effort consists of recompiling the source code, but sometimes it is necessary to rewrite major parts of the software.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] Many language specifications describe implementation defined behaviour (e.g. right shifting a signed integer in C can do a logical or an arithmetic shift).
[src:emscripten/software-portability] Operating system functions or third party libraries might not be available on the target system.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] Some functions can be available on a target system, but exhibit slightly different behavior such as `utime()` fails under Windows with EACCES, when it is called for a directory).
[src:emscripten/software-portability] The program code can contain unportable things, like the paths of include files, drive letters, or the backslash.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] Implementation defined things like byte order and the size of an int can also raise the porting effort.
[src:emscripten/software-portability] In practice the claim of languages, like C and C++, to have the WOCA (write once, compile anywhere) is arguable.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] A source-to-source translator converts between programming languages that operate at approximately the same level of abstraction, while a traditional compiler translates from a higher level language to a lower level language.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] For example, a source-to-source translator may perform a translation of a program from Python to JavaScript, while a traditional compiler translates from a language like C to assembly or Java to bytecode.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] An automatic parallelizing compiler will frequently take in a high level language program as an input and then transform the code and annotate it with parallel code annotations (e.g., OpenMP) or language constructs (e.g.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] Another purpose of source-to-source-compiling is translating legacy code to use the next version of the underlying programming language or an application programming interface (API) that breaks backward compatibility.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] Transcompilers may either keep translated code structure as close to the source code as possible to ease development and debugging of the original source code or may change the structure of the original code so much that the translated code does not look like the source code.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] Examples include Closure Compiler, CoffeeScript, Dart, Haxe, Opal, TypeScript and Emscripten.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] So called *Assembly language translators* are a class of source-to-source translators converting code from one assembly language into another, including (but not limited to) across different processor families and system platforms.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] Intel marketed their 16-bit processor 8086 to be source compatible to the 8080, an 8-bit processor.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] To support this, Intel had an ISIS-II-based translator from 8080 to 8086 source code named CONV86 (also referred to as CONV-86 and CONVERT 86) available to OEM customers since 1978, possibly the earliest program of this kind.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] It supported multiple levels of translation and ran at 2 MHz on an Intel Microprocessor Development System MDS-800 with 8-inch floppy drives.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] According to user reports, it did not work very reliably.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] Seattle Computer Products (SCP) offered TRANS86.COM, written by Tim Paterson in 1980 while developing 86-DOS.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] Also, performing only a mere transliteration, the brute-force single-pass translator did not carry out any register and jump optimizations.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] The SCP version 1 of TRANS86.COM ran on Z80-based systems.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] Once 86-DOS was running, Paterson, in a self-hosting-inspired approach, utilized TRANS86 to convert itself into a program running under 86-DOS.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] Numbered version 2, this was named TRANS.COM instead.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] Later in 1982, the translator was apparently also available from Microsoft.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] Also named TRANS86, Sorcim offered an 8080 to 8086 translator as well since December 1980.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] Like SCP's program it was designed to port CP/M-80 application code (in ASM, MAC, RMAC or ACT80 assembly format) to MS-DOS (in a format compatible with ACT86).
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] In ACT80 format it also supported a few Z80 mnemonics.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] The translation occurred on an instruction-by-instruction basis with some optimization applied to conditional jumps.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] The program ran under CP/M-80, MP/M-80 and Cromemco DOS with a minimum of 24 KB of RAM, and had no restrictions on the source file size.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] Much more sophisticated and the first to introduce optimizing compiler technologies into the source translation process was Digital Research's XLT86 1.0 in September 1981.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] The program was written by Gary Kildall and translated .ASM source code for the Intel 8080 processor (in a format compatible with ASM, MAC or RMAC assemblers) into .A86 source code for the 8086 (compatible with ASM86).
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] XLT86.COM itself was written in PL/I-80 for CP/M-80 platforms.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] The program occupied 30 KB of RAM for itself plus additional memory for the program graph.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] On a 64 KB memory system, the maximum source file size supported was about 6 KB, so that larger files had to be broken down accordingly before translation.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] Alternatively, XLT86 was also available for DEC VAX/VMS.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] Although XLT86's input and output worked on source-code level, the translator's in-memory representation of the program and the applied code optimizing technologies set the foundation to binary recompilation.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] 2500 AD Software offered an 8080 to 8086 source-code translator as part of their XASM suite for CP/M-80 machines with Z80 as well as for Zilog ZEUS and Olivetti PCOS systems.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] Since 1979, Zilog offered a Z80 to Z8000 translator as part of their PDS 8000 development system.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] Advanced Micro Computers (AMC) and 2500 AD Software offered Z80 to Z8000 translators as well.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] The latter was named TRANS and was available for Z80 CP/M, CP/M-86, MS-DOS and PCOS.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] The Z88DK development kit provides a Z80 to i486 source code translator targeting nasm named "to86.awk", written in 2008 by Stefano Bodrato.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] It is in turn based on an 8080 to Z80 converter written in 2003 by Douglas Beattie, Jr., named "toz80.awk".
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] In 2021, Brian Callahan wrote an 8080 CP/M 2.2 to MS-DOS source code translator targeting nasm named 8088ify.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] The first implementations of some programming languages started as transcompilers, and the default implementation for some of those languages are still transcompilers.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] In addition to the table below, a CoffeeScript maintainer provides a list of languages that compile to JavaScript.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] When developers want to switch to a different language while retaining most of an existing codebase, it might be better to use a transcompiler compared to rewriting the whole software by hand.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] Depending on the quality of the transcompiler, the code may or may not need manual intervention in order to work properly.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] This is different from "transcompiled languages" where the specifications demand that the output source code always works without modification.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] All transcompilers used to port a codebase will expect manual adjustment of the output source code if there is a need to achieve maximum code quality in terms of readability and platform convention.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] A transcompiler pipeline is what results from *recursive transcompiling*.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] By stringing together multiple layers of tech, with a transcompile step between each layer, technology can be repeatedly transformed, effectively creating a distributed language independent specification.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] XSLT is a general-purpose transform tool that can be used between many different technologies, to create such a derivative code pipeline.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] By repeating this process, one can turn A → B → C → D → E → F and then back into A(v2).
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] Some information will be preserved through this pipeline, from A → A(v2), and that information (at an abstract level) demonstrates what each of the components A–F agree on.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] In each of the different versions that the transcompiler pipeline produces, that information is preserved.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] It might take on many different shapes and sizes, but by the time it comes back to A (v2), having been transcompiled six times in the pipeline above, the information returns to its original state.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] This information which survives the transform through each format, from A–F–A(v2), is (by definition) derivative content or derivative code.
[src:emscripten/source-to-source-compiler] There are also debugging utilities that map the transcompiled source code back to the original code; for example, JavaScript source maps allow mapping of the JavaScript code executed by a web browser back to the original source in a transcompiled-to-JavaScript language.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] The main goal of WebAssembly is to facilitate high-performance applications on web pages, but it is also designed to be usable in non-web environments.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] It is an open standard intended to support any language on any operating system, and in practice many of the most popular languages already have at least some level of support.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Announced in 2015 (2015) and first released in March 2017 (2017-03), WebAssembly became a World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) recommendation on 5 December 2019 and it received the *Programming Languages Software Award* from the Association for Computing Machinery (ACM) SIGPLAN in 2021.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] The W3C maintains the standard with contributions from Mozilla, Microsoft, Google, Apple, Fastly, Intel, and Red Hat.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] The name "WebAssembly" is intended to suggest bringing assembly language programming to the World Wide Web, where it will be executed client-side, by the website-user's computer via the user's web browser.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] To accomplish this, WebAssembly must be much more hardware-independent than a true assembly language.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] WebAssembly was first announced in 2015, and the first demonstration was executing Unity's *Angry Bots* in Firefox, Google Chrome, and Microsoft Edge [Legacy].
[src:emscripten/webassembly] The precursor technologies were asm.js from Mozilla and Google Native Client, and the initial implementation was based on the feature set of asm.js.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] In March 2017, the design of the minimum viable product (MVP) was declared to be finished and the preview phase ended.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] In late September 2017, Safari 11 was released with support.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] In February 2018, the WebAssembly Working Group published three public working drafts for the Core Specification, JavaScript Interface, and Web API.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] The MVP was focused on low-level languages such as C and C++, with the intent to add features useful for high-level languages in a future version.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] The WebAssembly 2.0 specification was finished in 2022 and became a W3C standard in December 2024.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] It adds many single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) related instructions and a new v128 datatype, with the ability for functions to return multiple values, mass memory initialize/copy instructions, and reference types, which are opaque pointers to objects outside of the linear memory.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] WebAssembly 3.0 was released in September 2025.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] New features include a 64-bit address space, multiple address spaces, exception handling, and garbage collected struct and array types.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Support for garbage collection enables more efficient compiling for high-level languages, but WasmGC from WebAssembly 3.0 lacks the abilities needed by .NET runtime.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] While WebAssembly was initially designed to permit near-native code execution speed in the web browser, it has been considered valuable outside of such, in more generalized contexts.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] A WebAssembly runtime environment is a low-level virtual stack machine, akin to JVM or Flash VM; it can be embedded into any host application, and thus there have been created standalone WebAssembly runtime environments, including Wasmtime , WebAssembly Micro Runtime , Wasmer , WasmEdge and wazero .
[src:emscripten/webassembly] In November 2017, Mozilla declared support "in all major browsers", after WebAssembly was enabled by default in Edge [Legacy] 16.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] This support also includes mobile web browsers for iOS and Android.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] As of March 2024, 99% of tracked web browsers support WebAssembly (version 1.0), more than for its predecessor asm.js.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] For some extensions, from the 2.0 draft standard, support may be lower, but still more than 90% of web browsers may already support, e.g. the reference types extension.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Non-browser WebAssembly runtimes include Wasmer, Wasmtime, WAMR, WAVM, wasm3, and others.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] These systems execute precompiled Wasm modules and often provide additional APIs for embedding WebAssembly in different environments.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Use cases for wasm outside the browser include plug-in interfaces and lightweight virtualization.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] WebAssembly implementations generally use either ahead-of-time (AOT) or just-in-time (JIT) compiling, though some may also use an interpreter.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] While the first implementations appeared in web browsers, there are now many non-browser implementations for general-purpose use.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Because WebAssembly executables are precompiled, a variety of programming languages can target Wasm.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Compiling is done either through direct output to Wasm or via intermediate virtual machines implemented in Wasm.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] As of 2021, around 40 programming languages support WebAssembly as a compiling target.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Web browsers prevent WebAssembly code from directly manipulating the Document Object Model.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Wasm code must defer to JavaScript for this.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] In an October 2023 survey of developers, less than half of the 303 participants were satisfied with the state of WebAssembly.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] A large majority cited the need for improvement in four areas: § WASI, debugging support, integration with JavaScript and browser APIs, and build tooling.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] All major browsers allow WebAssembly if `Content-Security-Policy` is not specified, or if the value `unsafe-eval` is used, but behave differently otherwise; Chrome *requires* `unsafe-eval`, though a worker thread can be a workaround.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] In June 2018, a security researcher presented the possibility of using WebAssembly to circumvent browser mitigations for Spectre and Meltdown security vulnerabilities once support for threads with shared memory is added.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Due to this concern, WebAssembly developers put the feature on hold.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] However, in order to explore these future language extensions, Google Chrome added experimental support for the WebAssembly thread proposal in October 2018.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] WebAssembly has been criticized for allowing greater ease of hiding the evidence for malware writers, scammers and phishing attackers; WebAssembly is present on the user's machine only in its compiled form, which "[makes malware] detection difficult".
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Speed and the easy ability to conceal in WebAssembly have led to its use in hidden crypto mining within the website visitor's device.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] An April 2021 study from Universität Stuttgart found that since then crypto mining has been marginalized, falling to below 1% of all WebAssembly modules gathered from a wide range of sources, also including the Alexa top 1 million websites.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] As WebAssembly supports only structured control flow, it is amenable toward security verification techniques including symbolic execution.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] In 2019, a group of researchers from the University of Massachusetts Amherst presented a comprehensive analysis of WebAssembly's performance compared to native code.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] The paper identified several reasons for this performance difference, including missing optimizations, code generation issues in WebAssembly compilers, and inherent limits of the WebAssembly platform.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] In 2022, it was determined by researchers that a Wasm program runs at about 120% of (or 20% faster than) the speed of a comparable JavaScript program.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Those findings align with the experience of a startup company named "Zaplib", whose founders summarized in a blog that it was shutting down due to lack of performance in WebAssembly.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Their goal had been to significantly increase the performance of existing web apps by incrementally porting them to Rust/Wasm; however, porting a customer's simulator from JavaScript yielded only a 5% improvement in performance.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Benchmarking has revealed several other pain-points for WebAssembly, such as poor performance because of no direct access to the DOM, a problem which is being addressed.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] WebAssembly System Interface (WASI) is a simple interface (application binary interface (ABI) and application programming interface (API)) designed by Mozilla, which is intended to be portable to any platform.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] It provides features similar to the Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX), such as file input/output (I/O) constrained by capability-based security.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] WASI is influenced by CloudABI and Capsicum.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Solomon Hykes, a co-founder of Docker, wrote in 2019, "If WASM+WASI existed in 2008, we wouldn't have needed to create Docker.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] WASI 0.1 provides a few POSIX-like APIs such as file I/O, reading environment variables, and random-number generation, but has very little support for networking.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] WASI 0.2 is redesigned based on the WebAssembly Component Model.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] WASI 0.3 will add support for async functions; the host translates between blocking and async function calls, so an exported function that blocks may be called as an asynchronous function, and vice-versa.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Starting in 0.2, WASI is defined in terms of the component model.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Interfaces in the component model are specified in an IDL called WIT (WebAssembly Interface Types).
[src:emscripten/webassembly] While core wasm only supports integer and floating-point numbers, interfaces in WIT can express types such as strings, lists, and user-defined record and variant types, and are language-agnostic.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Components cannot access each other's memory, and so interact only via imported and exported functions.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] The component model is designed around composition: two components can be composed into a single component when the exports of one component match another's imports, allowing any interface to be virtualized.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Interfaces in WIT are grouped together into a "world".
[src:emscripten/webassembly] WASI 0.2 defines a CLI world similar to the POSIX-like API of WASI 0.1, and an HTTP proxy world for web servers.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] The component model is not currently supported by browsers.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] The general standard provides core specifications for the JavaScript API and details on embedding.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Wasm code (binary code, i.e. bytecode) is intended to be run on a portable virtual stack machine (VM).
[src:emscripten/webassembly] The VM is designed to be faster to parse and execute than JavaScript and to have compact code representation.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Any external functionality (like syscalls) that may be expected by Wasm binary code is not stipulated by the standard; instead, the standard specifies how the host environment can provide such an interface via a "module".
[src:emscripten/webassembly] A Wasm program is designed as a separate module containing collections of various Wasm-defined values and program type definitions.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] These are provided in either binary or textual format (see below) that have a common structure.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Such a module may provide a start function that is executed upon instantiation of a wasm binary.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] The list of instruction types includes those for standard memory load/store, numeric, parametric, control flow, and Wasm-specific variables.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] The number of opcodes used in the original standard (§ MVP) was a bit fewer than 200 of the 256 possible opcodes.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Subsequent versions of WebAssembly pushed the number of opcodes a bit over 200.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] The WebAssembly SIMD proposal (for parallel processing) introduces an alternate opcode prefix (0xfd) for 128-bit wide SIMD instructions; the concatenation of the SIMD prefix, plus an opcode that is valid after the SIMD prefix, forms each SIMD opcode.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] These SIMD opcodes are both portable and intended to map directly to native instruction sets like x86-64 and ARM.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] In contrast, SIMD instructions are not directly supported by Java's JVM or .NET's CIL; however, both do have some APIs for parallel processing, which provide SIMD speedups.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] A newer set of "relaxed SIMD" instructions allow for a limited amount of implementation-defined behavior to improve performance.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] In March 2017, the WebAssembly Community Group reached consensus on the initial ("MVP") binary format, JavaScript API, and reference interpreter.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] It defines a WebAssembly binary format (`.wasm`), which is designed to be used by computers, not humans, and a text format that is human-readable (`.wat`), resembling a cross between S-expressions and traditional assembly languages.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] The binary format is straightforward and designed to allow streaming compiling, so compiling can begin before the module is finished downloading, and to allow functions to be compiled in parallel.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] All integer constants are encoded using a space-efficient, variable-length LEB128 encoding.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] The WebAssembly text format is more canonically written in a folded format using S-expressions.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] For instructions and expressions, this format is purely syntactic sugar and has no behavioral differences with the linear format.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] A module is implicitly generated by the compiler.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] The function is referenced by an entry of the type table in the binary, hence a type section and the `type` emitted by the decompiler.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] The compiler and decompiler can be accessed online.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Data in memory is stored in a large, growable array of bytes termed a *linear memory*.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Linear memory is separate from the wasm module's call stack and code and the engine's memory.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] This allows running wasm code in the same process as the JavaScript virtual machine it's embedded in without violating memory safety.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] A module contains a list of global variables separate from linear memory, which may be mutable or immutable.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Functions declare a list of local variables.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] A function's parameters are also local variables.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Instructions operate on a stack of values.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] The stack layout is fixed (branches must push and pop the same number of operands), so wasm engines can compile the stack away, producing efficient machine code operations on registers, rather than managing a stack at runtime.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] A stack machine architecture was chosen as it can have higher code density than a register machine.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Unlike typical assembly languages, wasm only uses structured control flow similar to high-level programming languages.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] The intentional lack of support for jump instructions makes it simple to validate and compile wasm code in a single pass, and makes it easier to read code disassembled into the text format.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Blocks are delimited with the `block`, `loop`, and `if`/`else` constructs.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Branch instructions contain a label that identifies the depth of a block it is nested in: `br 0` will branch to the block the instruction is contained in, `br 1` will branch to the block that block is contained in, and so on.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Branches to a `block` or `if` jump to the end of the block like a break statement, while branches to a `loop` jump back to the *beginning* of the loop, similar to a continue statement.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] The `br_table` instruction takes an input index and jumps to a target from a list of labels.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] A C-style switch statement can be expressed with a `br_table` inside a series of nested blocks.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Compilers targeting wasm convert unstructured control flow into high-level loops using Emscripten's Relooper algorithm, originally designed to target JavaScript.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Function declarations are listed in a separate section before the section containing the function bodies.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Function pointers are emulated using an index into the global functions table, since code is not inside the linear memory.
[src:emscripten/webassembly] Functions can also be imported and exported, providing the foreign function interface to communicate with JavaScript or other embedders.
